{
  "phase": "confirmation",
  "confirmed_source": {
    "title": "First Father-Son Fight Extended Sequence",
    "publisher": "Image Comics (Skybound imprint)",
    "series": "Invincible",
    "issues": "#11-13",
    "year": 2004,
    "writer": "Robert Kirkman",
    "artist": "Ryan Ottley (primary artist), Cory Walker (co-creator/character designs)",
    "era": "Modern Age (2004)"
  },
  "story_summary": "Following the massacre of the Guardians of the Globe, Omni-Man finally reveals his true Viltrumite heritage to his son Mark. What begins as an uncomfortable conversation explodes into the most brutal father-son battle in comic book history. Across three issues, Nolan beats Mark mercilessly through city streets, subway tunnels, and past innocent civilians — including the infamous train scene where their bodies split a train car in half. The fight is one-sided devastation, with every punch carrying the weight of imperial duty against fatherly hesitation. In the end, Nolan leaves his son broken but alive — unable to kill the only thing he truly loved on Earth. Mark is left floating in the vacuum of space, watching his father abandon everything. It's a deconstruction of the Superman mythos, a story about duty versus love, and the moment Invincible truly becomes a hero.",
  "scene_outline": [
    {
      "scene_id": 1,
      "beat": "Hook: The revelation on the rooftop — Nolan reveals his Viltrumite conquest mission to Mark, who refuses to join him",
      "estimated_seconds": 8
    },
    {
      "scene_id": 2,
      "beat": "First strike: Nolan throws the first punch. The shock of a son realizing his father is about to kill him",
      "estimated_seconds": 7
    },
    {
      "scene_id": 3,
      "beat": "Through the city: The fight explodes across rooftops. Nolan dominates completely. Mark's desperate attempts to fight back are useless",
      "estimated_seconds": 10
    },
    {
      "scene_id": 4,
      "beat": "The subway: They crash underground. Civilians caught in the crossfire. The brutality escalates",
      "estimated_seconds": 8
    },
    {
      "scene_id": 5,
      "beat": "The train: The infamous moment where Nolan uses Mark's body to slice through a passing train — the ultimate horror of collateral damage",
      "estimated_seconds": 10
    },
    {
      "scene_id": 6,
      "beat": "Back to the surface: More destruction. Buildings crumble. Mark is bloodied, broken, barely conscious",
      "estimated_seconds": 7
    },
    {
      "scene_id": 7,
      "beat": "Nolan's monologue: Between blows, Nolan explains Viltrumite philosophy. Mark refuses to accept it",
      "estimated_seconds": 8
    },
    {
      "scene_id": 8,
      "beat": "The climax: Nolan has Mark beaten completely. The choice: kill his son or betray his empire",
      "estimated_seconds": 10
    },
    {
      "scene_id": 9,
      "beat": "The decision: Nolan can't do it. A single tear? A moment of hesitation. He leaves Earth instead",
      "estimated_seconds": 8
    },
    {
      "scene_id": 10,
      "beat": "Aftermath: Mark floats in space, broken, watching his father disappear. The weight of what just happened sinks in",
      "estimated_seconds": 10
    }
  ],
  "total_scenes": 10,
  "estimated_duration_seconds": 86,
  "tone": "Devastating, visceral, emotionally raw — a brutal deconstruction of the superhero father-son dynamic",
  "narrator_style": "Heavy, somber, building to horror, then landing on tragedy. Think Keith David narrating a nightmare",
  "message_to_user": "Here's my plan for the video. I've outlined 10 scenes covering the extended fight from Invincible #11-13. The tone will be devastating and visceral, capturing the horror of a father systematically beating his son across a city. Does this look good? Would you like me to adjust anything — emphasize the train scene more, expand on Nolan's internal conflict, or shift the ending focus?"
}
